It seems that in the old days produce of the interior of North
queensland moved over rough roads by bullook drawn carts which descended from the
"Table Land" to the Port of Douglas.
Then came the rail road to Cairnes and that
was the end of Port Douglas. As you get around the world it is rather sad to see
how changes beyond the control of the individual erode values.
I remember when Id
queeney of Monsanto Chemical said that one of the dad effects of chemical research
was the damage done to some old established businesses such, for example, as the
leather trade or sponge divers. This reation is evident in the local economy
where the formerly important pearl button industry has been almost wholly, supplanted
by plastios.
As a result the Queensland government had been experimenting with the
culture of artifioial pearls. They have haddquite a bit of help from the Japanese
in return for which technical assistance the Japs take over the marketing of the
pearls, at which, they are most experienced and I suspect reap the largest share of
the profit.
One of the fringe benefits of our travels in the tropios has been the Paw Paws
or Papayas. For 30 years I have tried in vain to like them but not until this trip
did I succeed. Also the Australian Mangos are as good as we have ever tasted.
Deo. 29%h. This year Christnes for us is just the 25th of Begember, but we're
neither homesick or unhappy. Yesterday we hired a car and driver and motored up
to the Table Lands about 1200 feet higher than Cairnes which of course is a sea level
port and at sea level. We saw "the most beautiful rail road station in the world"
and by golly it lived up to its billing. The station itself was much like any other
American station with tracks on either side but the entire 150 - 200 foot length was
done quite a bit of prospecting. He told us all about the old days before the rail
road, the bullock carts and the early pioneers of whom his father was one. He asked
him about the aborigines, whom he called "abos", who are much more in evidence in
this part of Australia than elsewbere. I told him that Capt. Cook had to put in to
shore for pepairs
to his ship just notth of here and was much surprised to find no
natives at all nor did any come around for the whole three months he was there. Our
driver said that was because the abos lived up on the Table Land where they lead a
nomadic life following the game and fishing in the numerous streams.
In fact he
said that one quite intelligent abo said to him" You know, sir, you white people
are making real progress - you do not work as hard as your father did and he in turn
did not work as hard as his father.
With us it is just the reverse. My grandfather
didn't do any work at all.
He had a good life. Then when the white man came my
father had to work, he
couldn't just nove around hunting and fishing.
Then I came
along and I have to work much harder than my father did. We abos are sliding back
as fast as you whites are going ahead."
Ded. 26th, En route Cairns - Thursday Island. We are flying in a twin engined
Fokker along the coast with the Great Barrier Reef clearly marked off, to our right
ship - is off to our right.

engagements of World War II was fought. We were sort of hoping to
fly over to Papua and New Guinea. We had heard that up in the mountains at a place
called Goroka there would be a big gathering of tribesmen and a most interesting show.
We actually applied for a permit to fly to Port Morenby but we then learned that the
bie pow pow of natives had been called off and that we might have alot of trouble
securing permits to go beyond Port Moresby because of trouble with Sukarno over the
border between Australia and Indonesia. While there may be no real trouble you can
sure get plenty of run around from the bureaucrats who control the granting of travel
permits.
So tonight we'll be with Debby's friend Reg Seott and tomorrow we'll fly as
far as Hockhampton.
It would have been intensely interesting to see the areas in New
Guinea where B1ll Hawkins spent so much time during
the war and perhaps get over to
Rabaul and the Solonon Islands where Bill Barrett operated his P.T. boat so effectively
but that will have to wait.
